{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c2e0cd11-e7ed-47f7-b28b-2baa99f38909","content":"**.NET MAUI Android ignores `JAVA_HOME`.** It uses its own JDK discovery and expects the **Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17**, not Adoptium Temurin.\n\n**Fix — pick one:**\n\n1. **Install the Microsoft JDK** (recommended):\n   ```bash\n   brew install --cask microsoft-openjdk17\n   ```\n   MAUI will find it automatically.\n\n2. **Or force MAUI to use your Temurin JDK** by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\nOption 1 is the path of least resistance — it's what the toolchain expects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"83463fce-fef9-4ce0-9d99-4b37ca774036","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what the common issue is here.\n\nThis is a well-known issue: .NET MAUI (and Xamarin.Android) Android builds require a specific JDK. Starting with .NET 8+, the Android SDK build tools require JDK 17, but there's a specific issue with .NET MAUI and the JDK distribution.\n\nActually, the most common issue is that .NET Android (used by MAUI) ships with its own Microsoft OpenJDK distribution and expects to use that. If JAVA_HOME points to a different JDK, it can cause issues.\n \nOn macOS specifically, Adoptium Temurin installs to a nested path structure under `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/`, and the real issue is often that JAVA_HOME isn't pointing to the correct `Contents/Home` subdirectory. The core problem usually comes down to either a JDK version mismatch or a conflict between using Microsoft's bundled OpenJDK versus a third-party distribution like Adoptium. The real issue is likely that .NET MAUI's build system bypasses JAVA_HOME entirely and uses its own JDK detection logic, controlled by the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property—so even if Temurin 17 is properly installed, MAUI might be picking up a different or incompatible JDK version, or the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the workload isn't being recognized correctly. the user says they have Temurin 17.0.12, so that's not the version mismatch issue. I'm probably overthinking this—they didn't actually share the error message, so I should focus on the most common culprit: MAUI on macOS typically doesn't automatically pick up JAVA_HOME and instead looks for Microsoft OpenJDK in specific locations. The straightforward solution is either installing Microsoft OpenJDK 17 via Homebrew or explicitly configuring MSBuild to use their existing JDK. Temurin by setting `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in the csproj file. This is the most straightforward solution—either install Microsoft OpenJDK directly or point the build property to an existing Temurin installation.","outputTokens":1585,"requestId":"A42A:B2E8D:5D3D8A9:65B8240:69F004EA"},"id":"4fa52892-eb5a-4bc2-8732-807f1da53180","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:53:30.062Z","parentId":"98dc521f-acfb-4eaa-b0cb-719b00ae292d"}
